title: Sesame Seared Tuna With Vegetable Slaw
summary: Sesame Seared Tuna With Vegetable Slaw is a gluten free and pescatarian main course. This recipe serves 4 and costs $5.48 per serving. One serving contains 548 calories, 40g of protein, and 23g of fat. This recipe is liked by 1 foodies and cooks. Head to the store and pick up sesame seeds, bell peppers, rice vinegar, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the vanilla bean you could follow this main course with the Mini Vanilla Scones with Vanilla Bean Glaze as a dessert. It can be enjoyed any time, but it is especially good for The Fourth Of July. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes approximately 40 minutes. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 90%. This score is amazing. Similar recipes are Sesame Seared Tuna, Pan-seared Sesame-crusted Tuna, and Seared Sesame-crusted Tuna.

winePairing.pairingText: Merlot, Pinot Noir, and rosé Wine are my top picks for Tuna. Though fish is often paired with white wine, 'meatier' fish like tuna can absolutely go with red wine. A Rosé will also pair nicely, particularly if your tunan is prepared with ingredients better suited to a white wine. One wine you could try is Duckhorn Napa Valley Merlot. It has 4.2 out of 5 stars and a bottle costs about 58 dollars.

productMatches.title: Duckhorn Napa Valley Merlot
productMatches.description: This wine shows aromas of sweet plum sauce, vanilla, chocolate, cedar and butterscotch with big, forward black cherry and black berry fruit in the mouth. A balanced middle with a hint of toasty oak is paired with a nice bite from rounded tannins, and a long pleasant finish. This wine pairs well with grilled meats and wild game with herb-infused, wild-berry sauces, hearty pasta dishes and Pacific Northwest Salmon.

instructions: For slaw and dressingAttach grating blade to food processor. Julienne each vegetable and set aside. In another bowl, mix all dressing ingredients and add vegetables. Add cilantro and combine gently. Let rest for at least 30 minutes.For tunaPlace a large nonstick pan over high heat until hot. Combine sesame seeds and wasabi in a bowl; season with salt and pepper. Coat pan with cooking spray; drizzle oil in pan. Lightly salt tuna; dredge in sesame-wasabi mixture. Reduce heat to medium and place tuna in pan. Sear until lightly browned, about 2 minutes. Flip; cook 2 minutes more. Remove from heat and let rest for a few minutes. Divide slaw among 4 plates and top with tuna.Source: The Lincoln, Santa Monica, CAAttach grating blade to food processor.
